Only root vegetables like carrots with a long tap root or potatoes need to be sown directly into the ground.  Most other plants will grow very well being planted in trays indoors first and then transplanted into the garden once they've reached a good size.  You can better control the temperature, water and light and keep them away from pests while they're most vulnerable.

[Eden Seeds](https://www.edenseeds.com.au/) and [Diggers](https://www.diggers.com.au/) have a great range of quality heirloom seed.

## Soil

You can learn what healthy soil looks like by observing a forest floor.  Plant life has thrived on earth without human intervention.  As plant and animal life die they fall on top of the ground, decompose and break down into food for fungi, insects and and micro organisms.  The top soil is kept covered with leaves, branches and plants.

Putting 1-2 inches of compost on the top of your soil once a year is all you need.  You can add organic fertilisers but they're not required for strong healthy plants.  Healthy soil will grow healthy plants.

[Charles Dowding - No dig explained in 3 minutes](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VJhGIrqKs1k)

Home made compost is the best thing for your garden, it's free and it saves waste from going to landfill too.
Hot composting is the fastest method but you do need a fair amount of material(1m cube) to generate enough heat for it to work properly.  It will still work with less, it'll just take longer and isn't as nice to work with.
Simply pile up any plant materials like grass, kitchen scraps, wood chips and coffee grounds into a big heap and wait.
Turning the pile will speed up the process but isn't required.

