## Sun

Non intuitively more of a plants structure comes from the air rather than the soil.
The leaves pull carbon out of the air with energy from the Sun.
Most plants grow best in full direct sun, leafy greens and herbs are the exceptions that can grow well with less.

## Water

2-3 times a week should be enough for most plants.  You want to keep on top of the watering in the early stages of growth and then you can taper off and water less in the later stages. Overwatering can lead to less flavourful fruit and delayed harvest.
Water around the base of the plants where possible, watering leaves can encourage fungal  diseases.

## Pests

Keep an eye on the garden and watch what's happening.  When you're watering look out for signs of damage or larvae.  In an organic garden you should expect to suffer some losses to pests or disease but you shouldn't ever need to use any pesticides.

- Netting and covers for birds.
- Picking off slugs and caterpillars by hand.
- Using a dish soap spray for flying insects like aphids.

## Harvest

Pick early and often.  You can harvest at any time, you don't need to wait for things to reach their full size.  Lots of plants give a continual harvest meaning you don't need to pull up the plant to harvest. Lettuces for example you can pick the lower leaves and it will keep growing.  Broccoli will send up side shoots after the main head which you can keep harvesting.

